article.headline: Loyola of Chicago 69, Wis.-Green Bay 52
article.story: GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Majak Kou scored all of his 19 points in the first half, as Loyola of Chicago beat Wisconsin-Green Bay 69-52 in a Horizon League game Saturday night. The Ramblers (17-9, 8-5 Horizon) used a 21-0 run in which Green Bay (14-12, 6-7) was held scoreless for a stretch of 11:13 to take a commanding 39-14 halftime lead. The Phoenix finished the first half an abysmal 6-of-29 (20.7 percent) from the field, while the Ramblers hit 17-of-29 (58.6 percent) first-half attempts. Green Bay showed signs of life early in the second half, going on a 10-4 run, but the Phoenix was never in serious contention. Blake Schilb had 11 points, 10 assists and six rebounds for Loyola. Tom Levin added 10 points off the bench and J.R. Blount grabbed 10 rebounds. Aswan Minatee scored 11 points and had six rebounds off the bench to lead the Phoenix. Ryan Evanochko, Ryan Tillema and Mike Schachtner each added nine points. A win would have put the Phoenix in a tie with the Ramblers for third place in the league. Instead, Loyola has a two-game lead and the tiebreaker over Green Bay with three league games remaining. A top-three finish is important because the top three teams get a first-round bye in the conference tournament.
